metadata.name: Before the Storm #29
metadata.description:
"Before the Storm" captures a fleeting moment of calmness amidst an impending tempest. Heavy clouds loom overhead, suffusing the air with palpable moisture and an alluring aroma. Majestic evergreens stand tall and proud, bravely facing the ominous yet strangely inviting sky. The air crackles with electrifying energy, foreshadowing the raw power of nature about to be unleashed. In this fleeting moment, one cannot help but be mesmerized by the sublime forces at play, but beware, the calm will not last forever.

Technical Note:
If you wish to render a high-quality version of your iteration, I strongly recommend increasing the resolution (press "R") and setting anti-aliasing to >1 (press "A"). However, be aware that it might take longer to compile and may not render at all on older hardware. To save the image, press "S".

The code has been tested on my old MacBook and on various Windows machines. For best results, use a modern Chromium-based browser, and make sure your browser supports WebGL 2.

metadata.name: FXHASH Generative Logo #245
metadata.description:
Unique iteration of the first Generative Token minted on fxhash.

It also servers as the actual logo of the platform. It represents the generative processes driving fxhash tokens. Generative Tokens are fed with a unique hash to produce unique outputs based on the hash — they are functions with a hash as single input.

The growth that comes out of the text is driven by a "Dividing-Aggregating Walkers" (DAW) algorithm. The hash drives all the DAW settings, as well as a mutation factor which is responsible for changes in each Walker parameters as they divide.

Some iterations will produce very simple outputs whereas others might be more chaotic.

Piece by @ciphrd for fxhash

metadata.name: Mooncakes: Happy Mid Autumn Festival 2022 #3566
metadata.description:
To celebrate the Moon Festival with Mooncakes, we have created a quest to introduce everyone to fxhash. As part of that quest on mooncakes.fun, users are encouraged to mint this generative token.

This is a layered image composition using the Mooncakes site images on a 1920x1080 canvas. The image elements are randomly assigned position, scale, tint, and blur according to a ruleset which generates a Mid Autumn Festival scene made up of: Moon, Clouds, Stars, Lanterns, and Lotuses.

Special filters, shapes and colors are included as rare features, as well as a couple of surprises.

metadata.name: Flooded Harmony #95
metadata.description:
"Flooded Harmony", the second project of the Harmony collection. 
While we continue to produce new pieces from this Harmony collection, we strive to push the boundaries and show the different concepts in our new collections.
We're excited to introduce our new collections in near future that are totally different!

This piece features a dynamic color palette that seamlessly blends different shades to create a stunning visual experience. The day/night theme adds another layer of depth to the artwork, providing a glimpse into the duality of life. In addition to the theme and color palette, this NFT also offers different horizon heights, allowing you to see the artwork from various perspectives. 

Features:
- Different horizon heights
- Different Styles
- Day/Night Theme
- Multiple color palettes

metadata.name: Badgirs City #160
metadata.description:
"I used to live in a small city placed at the center of Iran's plateau with the warmest summer days in the country part; spending most of my childhood with my sweet grandma at her old house. She was always keeping her eyes on me not to get heat stroke at noon playing in the yard when the sun was at its peak glowing furiously. Sundays at noon were my favorite, I used to call them “Ice cream” noons sitting beside the nicest person you could imagine and enjoying a delightful ice cream. You won't know how lovely it was to have an ice cream relaxing under the most enjoyable cold breeze of the tallest windcatcher in the city at her house. "



The Badgirs city is the first collaboration between Fleep and IceRain on Fxhash. The concept was established first with the design of a school with a feeling of safe and nostalgia reminding us of the good memories of our childhood as the grandma’s house and the windcatcher for Fleep.
A windcatcher (Badgir) is an Iranian traditional architectural element in the form of a small tower built on the roof of houses in warm locations to create passive cooling. The collection of Badgirs city is a modern recreational development of those traditional windcatchers designed by Fleep and icerain and exquisitely translated into code by Icerain.

Controls:
[1] Set the resolution to Medium Resolution
[2] Set the resolution to High Resolution

metadata.name: Bound #144
metadata.description:
Knots bind and hold, mark time, and unite. But the power of a well-tied knot isn't only to fasten – it also symbolizes how tightly one holds their pledges. Whether a commitment to a partner, community, or oneself – the longevity of a deeply held bond is often marked with a symbol of passing time, like knots tied in a rope.

Let these ropes remind us of the binds we hold – new ones, lengthy ones, unbreakable ones, and even those we’ve had to untie. In plain view, these knots invite us to contemplate what our bonds mean to us, and to see them anew.

---

Press ‘1’-’9’ to increase resolution
Press 's' to save an image of the output at the current resolution

metadata.name: WOZ #4
metadata.description:
The Wonderful Wizard of Oz is a timeless story we’ve all grown to love. Written by L. Frank Baum in 1900, the novel has now entered the public domain. This NFT collection “WOZ” pays homage to the book, with a “utility-focused” approach.

Text-heavy NFTs are notoriously difficult to appreciate. Words are small, graphics are cluttered.

The WOZ collection rethinks how large amounts of text are consumed in NFT thumbnails. It allows readers to train their eyes to the center of the screen and find themselves absorbed in a stream of words.

Chapters, colors, and textures are randomly assigned at time of mint.

Controls:
up-arrow / swipe up = start
down-arrow / swipe down = pause
left-arrow / swipe left = slower
left-arrow / swipe right = faster
[secret letter] = toggle dark mode (computer-only)

metadata.name: The Fringe #16
metadata.description:
We are innately aware of our bodies' position through perception of space. If we are visibly surrounded by walls with flooring under, a ceiling above, and a window facing the sky, we know we are inside of an enclosed space, with a view of outside. But how does a room stopped being an enclosed space? Can a space with 3 walls be considered a room? If we are surrounded by walls but our ceiling is gone, then are we inside or outside? This is an exploration on the edges of our ability to perceive space. The fringes that instill some fear in our mind. And that fear is failing to make sense of our position in a space that slowly loses its tangibility.

------------
Press [s] to save captured image
------------
